      • saveBitmap

        public static void saveBitmap(java.lang.String filename,
                              android.graphics.Bitmap bmp)
        Saves a bitmap to the given filename

        To copy from phone to desktop:

        Shell 1: adb shell su whoami cp /data/user/0/com.locuslabs.android.sdk/files/actual-bitmap.bmp /sdcard/Download/ cp /data/user/0/com.locuslabs.android.sdk/files/expected-bitmap.bmp /sdcard/Download/

        Shell 2: adb pull /sdcard/Download/actual-bitmap.bmp ~/Desktop/ adb pull /sdcard/Download/expected-bitmap.bmp ~/Desktop/

        Parameters:
        filename -
        bmp -
        See Also:
        https://stackoverflow.com/questions/649154/save-bitmap-to-location

      • iIsInRangeIE

        public static boolean iIsInRangeIE(long i,
                                   long lowerInclusive,
                                   long upperExclusive)
        Checks that an integer is in range inclusive of the left but exclusive of the right. This is useful when you need to verify that an index is valid for an array.

        The I in the method name means the lower bound is inclusive The E in the method name means the upper bound is exclusive

        Parameters:
        i - the value you want to check, for example an index in an array
        lowerInclusive - the minimum value, inclusive, e.g. 0 for an array's lower bound
        upperExclusive - the maximum value, exclusive, e.g. array's size for upper bound
        Returns:

      • iIsInRangeII

        public static boolean iIsInRangeII(long i,
                                   long lowerInclusive,
                                   long upperInclusive)
        Checks that an integer is in range inclusive of the left and inclusive of the right. This is useful when you need to verify that a number is in a range given an upper and lower bound.

        The I in the method name means the lower bound is inclusive

        Parameters:
        i - the value you want to check
        lowerInclusive - the minimum value, inclusive
        upperInclusive - the maximum value, inclusive
        Returns:

      • calEQ

        public static boolean calEQ(java.util.Calendar x,
                            java.util.Calendar y)
        Performs Calendar.getTimeInMillis() comparison and returns if equal. This is an alternative to Calendar.equals(Object) which works better for comparing Calendar objects that have different time zones. Calendar.equals(Object) returns false if the TimeZones are different types (e.g. libcore.util.ZoneInfo vs. java.util.SimpleTimeZone) even if the time in millis is the same.
        Parameters:
        x - left operand
        y - right operand
        Returns:
        true/false if equal based on time in millis

      • calGT

        public static boolean calGT(java.util.Calendar x,
                            java.util.Calendar y)
        Performs Calendar.getTimeInMillis() comparison and returns if x is greater than y. See calEQ(Calendar, Calendar) for justification of using this over Calendar.after(Object)
        Parameters:
        x - left operand
        y - right operand
        Returns:
        true/false if x greater than y based on time in millis

      • calLT

        public static boolean calLT(java.util.Calendar x,
                            java.util.Calendar y)
        Performs Calendar.getTimeInMillis() comparison and returns if x is less than y. See calEQ(Calendar, Calendar) for justification of using this over Calendar.before(Object)
        Parameters:
        x - left operand
        y - right operand
        Returns:
        true/false if x less than y based on time in millis
